Selective Announcements in Screen Readers

02
On this page
  1. Update the Days of the Week
    1. Hide the Single Letters from Screen Readers
    2. Add Announcements for Hidden Text
  2. Checking our Work in VoiceOver
  3. Testing with NVDA on Windows

Starting up VoiceOver and tabbing over to the date picker in Safari, notice how much more semantic information is being announced.

The screen reader announced our new month label, as well as the structure of rows and columns.

Something that could be handled better is the header with the days of the week.

As of right now, VoiceOver announces only the first letter of the day. It would be more informative for the screen reader to announce the day’s full name.

Update the Days of the Week

Back in our code, let’s look at the date picker headers.

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
  <tr className="days-of-week">
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Sunday">S</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Monday">M</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Tuesday">T</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Wednesday">W</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Thursday">T</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Friday">F</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Saturday">S</span>
    </th>
  </tr>
</thead>
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
  <tr className="days-of-week">
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Sunday">S</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Monday">M</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Tuesday">T</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Wednesday">W</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Thursday">T</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Friday">F</span>
    </th>
    <th scope="col">
      <span title="Saturday">S</span>
    </th>
  </tr>
</thead>

The spans that wrap each day of the week have a title with the full day, but that information doesn’t make its way through to VoiceOver.

Let’s update the structure of the headers so that screen readers announce the full days of the week.

Hide the Single Letters from Screen Readers

Since the single letter spans are a visual aide for the date picker, let’s replace them with more descriptive text for screen readers.

The first thing we’ll do is add aria-hidden="true" to each of the spans to suppress their content.

To be extra sure that VoiceOver won’t try to announce them, setting the ARIA presentation role should remove its accessibility information.

Here’s the new structure of the table headers:

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
	<tr className="days-of-week">
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">S</span>
	  </th>
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">M</span>
	  </th>
		...
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
	<tr className="days-of-week">
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">S</span>
	  </th>
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">M</span>
	  </th>
		...

With this markup, the single letters will still be visible in the date picker but will not be announced in the screen reader.

Add Announcements for Hidden Text

In order to have the screen reader announce the days, we’ll create a new set of spans for the full day names with the visually-hidden class applied to them.

An element with this class added to it will still technically be rendered, so it will be available to screen readers.

The CSS for visually-hidden is already present in the global styles for the CampSpots app:

.visually-hidden {
    clip: rect(0 0 0 0);
    clip-path: inset(50%);
    height: 1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    position: absolute;
    white-space: nowrap;
    width: 1px;
}
.visually-hidden {
    clip: rect(0 0 0 0);
    clip-path: inset(50%);
    height: 1px;
    overflow: hidden;
    position: absolute;
    white-space: nowrap;
    width: 1px;
}

Here’s how the table header structure looks now:

// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
	<tr className="days-of-week">
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">S</span>
	    <span className="visually-hidden">Sunday</span>
	  </th>
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">M</span>
	    <span className="visually-hidden">Monday</span>
	  </th>
		...
// components/date-picker/date-picker.js
<thead>
	<tr className="days-of-week">
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">S</span>
	    <span className="visually-hidden">Sunday</span>
	  </th>
	  <th scope="col">
	    <span aria-hidden="true" role="presentation">M</span>
	    <span className="visually-hidden">Monday</span>
	  </th>
		...

Checking our Work in VoiceOver

Back in the browser, VoiceOver won’t announce the full day when arrowing through the cells.

However, when using VoiceOver’s table-specific navigation controls (CTRL + Option + Arrow keys) the full day is announced.

Testing with NVDA on Windows

One of the most popular combinations reported in the WebAIM Screen Reader Survey was NVDA with Chrome on Windows.

Using Parallels or similar virtual machine software on a Mac to run Windows, we can test the date picker in NVDA. This is made easier by plugging in a USB keyboard with a Windows layout.

Interacting with the date picker in NVDA works great. There’s even the nice feature of it announcing when the button select status changed, which is something that VoiceOver doesn’t support.
